review_blob: A crisp and full lager. A slightly heavier body than most lagers. Light lacing that didnt last too long. Almost buttery flavor. Not a lot more too it than that.
Poured a slightly umber brownish with a slight reddish. Head was light tan, off whitish. Flavor was a bit spicy, but full and not much aftertaste. Aroma was limited, and not over baring.
Poured almost a straight up brown, but with hints of copper. Head was thick and lasted quite a while. Flavor was good, full without a watery/empty taste
Overall not a bad lager. Poured a typical pale gold/yellow, with a fairly white head that didnt last very long. Highly carbonated, and watery but still flavorful.
An average beer with lots of carbonation, and an almost sweet taste. The malt is a bit more pervasive than other lagers of this quality. A slight hint of spiciness as well.

Poured a very hazy golden light brown. Had more of the visual characteristic of a wheat beer, though much darker in color. Aroma was mild and sweet. Flavor was not nearly as strong or sharp as youd expect from an IIPA, but very good. I would say fairly balanced for an IIPA

Poured a very dark brown that you could almost see through, and a very thick tan head that went away quickly, but left quite a bit on the glass. Taste was nutty chocolate, and fortunately for me lacked any coffee overtones

Poured a very dark red/amber with a particularly thick foamy head. Aroma was pleasant and not over powering. Flavor was very smooth and balanced. A good strong hop flavor, yet enough malt to not be a hop head special. Very good beer.

"Imperial IPAs are probably my favorite specific style of brew, and I would not call myself a hop head by any stretch, but very much liked this beer. The first one of the four pack seemed to have too much hops for my tastes, but the other three where quite good. Not much else I could add to the reviews, but it was very good.
For something called Hop House, not very hoppy. Average Pale Ale. Not a lot of character at all, but very drinkable. Would easily replace something much lighter as a good hot day drink.
For the first time in a while, I didnt bother pouring out of the bottle, so dont really know what it looks like, but the taste is fairly even and understated. Very drinkable
This beer looked good in the glass. A very brown-red that was almost not able to be seen through. The flavor was of an ale with a lot of malt in it, which I suppose that is to be expected.
beer_name: Moylans Dannys Irish Style Red Ale

review_blob: Poured a mild yellow, with a slightly off white head. Head diminished quickly, and left no lacing. Highly carbonated. I would call this an above average pale lager.
My first attempt at a Barelywine and I was happy with the outcome.  Poured a medium copper/brown color with a light foamy head.  A mild sweetness inner twined with the malty and a hint of the hops.

Bottle dated 2007, purchased 8/2009.
Blech!  Guess I should have heeded the warning about the maltyness.  Poured dark dark brownish red with a little bit of off white head that lasted maybe a minute.  Aroma was malty sweet.  Taste was all alcohol and bitterness.  Not my cup of tea.  I could have skipped this and been fine.

Very yummie. A strong hop and malt flavor, but not so over powering to get bitter beer face. There was something else going on flavor wise that I couldnt quite put my finger on, but it was for the good, not bad.

Purchased this brew at a local restaurant, and it was served is a extra tall pilsner glass. The head was minimal in size, but that could be due to delivery time or pour method as the head lasted quite a while. The color was a dark hazy copper. The taste more hop and not a lot of malt. Not much else to it. And contrary to the deScription list here, it did not good well with the very spicy Cuban pork sandwich I had for dinner.

I was intrigued by this beer, mostly from what it said on its label. When I poured it, it wasnt anything too special. Had the look of a heavier lager, slight hazy yellow with a large amount of carbonation. The head was tall, but the density was light, yet lasted. The aroma of the heather was obvious, and I had some trepidation as a rule, I dont like the smell of heather. The taste was light and not over powering. The flowery smell and flavor was obvious but not so much it killed. A nice out of the ordinary brew.

Well, originally I thought I was in for a treat when I purchased this brew. Unfortunately it was the wrong kind of treat. After reading some of the reviews here, Im thinking the one I had had turned. I was unable to get more than one sip. The smell was unbearable. Like one post said, old leather shoes soaked in soy sauce for a while. I think the thing that surprised me the most was that the bottle was actually blue.

Im still trying to figure out these dark lagers. The color is dark red, almost brown with a light head that didnt last too long. The flavor was smooth, and not over powering. Not much carbonation. Full flavor without some of the heaviness that you can get with IPAs and such.

This seemed to me to be a fairly average IPA. The hoppyness was mildly aggressive with the color and aroma being the high points. If I where going to volume, this would be the IPA to drink. Not as heavy as some, but its not flavored water either.
beer_name: Big Sky Scape Goat Pale Ale

review_blob: Pour dark yet almost opaque brown with a large tan head that disappeared quickly. Aroma was distinctive, yet not harsh or overpowering. Pleasant smell of hazelnuts (duh) and mild maltyness. Flavor was nutty with a bit of caramel chocolate.
A nice balanced beer with the hoppiness youd expect from a pale ale yet adds some malt flavor with some spices added in for good measure. Very drinkable beer.
beer_name: Samuel Smiths Organic / Old Brewery Pale Ale

review_blob: A good light weight beer. The strawberry was very subtle. More smelled it than tasted it, which is fine. Not a very strong hop taste, and little maltiness. Worked ok for a refreshment after playing baseball with the kids.

Poured yellow with a hint of orange, and a very white and thin head. Didnt look of much carbonation, but tasted like a lot. Flavor was thin and crisp. Would have been better if it was hot outside. Taste was mild to bland, but I think of most lagers that way.

Poured a yellowish copper with a mildly thick off white head that lasted only briefly. The aroma was all hops. The flavor was bitter like you would expect, but not so much so that it kills. Overall very good.

Hmmm...poured a dark golden yellow, as you would expect, with a mild head that dissipated quickly. As it set in the glass it looked at least above average. The taste again was what you would have expected from an average beer of this style. Nothing to jump out at you.

Having cut my teeth years ago on Irish Red (Weinhards), I have a partial bias toward the style. The color is a dark red amber. The head lasted for a good amount of time for a lager. Flavor is bold and full. Could drink these all day.

Poured just as you would expect, very dark brown with a light brown head that lingered quite a while. Aroma was strong with dark chocolate hints, and strong malty coffee. Unfortunately I dont like coffee at all. I was able to think past the coffee and enjoyed the rest of the smooth, heavy flavor.
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: What else can I say that already hasnt been said. Tastes much better than any other lager that Ive had. I finally bucked the "popular" trend and gave Sam a try. Should have a long time ago.

The pale golden color was reminiscent of things I dont like to drink any more, but there was a hint of more body to the color. Looked to have more carbonation than it tasted. Had the distinctive Pilsener aftertaste, but not as bad as the Macrobrews. Not my favorite style over all.

Well, I cheated and was lazy and didnt pour it into a glass. So I dont know what it looks like, but I really liked this one. There was the distinctive hoppiness you would expect from an IPA, but it didnt overbear or kill you with hops. Great beer. Goes well with Fritos.
beer_name: Lost Coast Indica India Pale Ale

review_blob: This was just an average IPA. Smelled and tasted of hops, but what would you expect from an IPA. Nothing bad, but nothing out of the ordinary. Just average.
A little above average for a mass market lager.  Slightly more too it flavor wise than others in this areana.

Overall a very good beer. When I first poured, I must not have been paying attention as I managed to fill the entire pint glass with foam. After figuring out how to pour, the color was an opaque chocolate brown. The head was a dark tan and lasted a while.

Poured a golden almost lager yellow with nearly a full glass of foam that lasted quite awhile. Flavor was very full and almost fruity. Not really sure what, but some real style ans substance to it. Not just watery.

This brew poured a light copper yellow with basically no head at all. Lots of carbonation that lasted through the end of the glass. Flavor was watery with a little bit of malt sharpness and a very understated hops bite
beer_name: Black Sheep Monty Pythons Holy Grail (Bottle)

review_blob: This is probably the most complex beer that Ive been able to tell what the complexities where. Partly a hop heavy IPA type flavor and mouthfeel, yet a spicy (coriander?) malty tastes as well. Very good. Obviously I couldnt wait til 12.12.12.
beer_name: Stone 20th Anniversary Encore Series: 08.08.08 Vertical Epic Ale

review_blob: Wanted something a little lighter to marinade tri-tip with so I gave this a try. I liked this lager as it had more body to it than most. Looks more IPAish, which I guess should be expected. A lot more carbonation that I would have liked, but the malt/hop balance over came than. Decent middle of the road beer.

Poured and looked like any standard stout, dark smooth though not with much head but a lot of carbonation. Much easier to drink for us dark beer novices. Not very bitter, very complex taste, with very little to no mocha or coffee taste (thank goodness!).
Pleasantly surprised by this beer. Poured a darkish amber color with a thick off white head that lasted most of the glass. Flavor was fairly mild and not over powering. Sufficient body in the taste
A milky white/hazy yellow color with a pale and long lasting head.  Taste of sweet and fruity.  Heavier mouth feel than you would expect.
beer_name: Blue Moon Honey Moon Summer Ale

review_blob: Too sweet and citriusy for my taste.  Aroma and appearance overstate the full quality of the beer.  Looks like it should have tasted better than it did.
Thick smooth mouthfeel.  Tastes thicker than it looks.  Dark burnt umber color, with a off white to almost tan head.
